SIMPLE: retrench
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Retrench
<hw>Re*trench"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Retrenched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Retrenching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>retrenchier</ets>, F. <ets>retrancher</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets>
re- + OF. <ets>trenchier</ets>, F. <ets>trancher</ets>, to cut. See
<er>Trench</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cut off; to pare
away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy exuberant parts <qex>retrench</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lessen; to abridge; to curtail; <as>as, to
<ex>retrench</ex> superfluities or expenses</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But this thy glory shall be soon <qex>retrenched</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To confine; to limit; to restrict.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These figures, ought they then to receive a <qex>retrenched</qex>
interpretation?</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>To furnish with a retrenchment;
<as>as, to <ex>retrench</ex> bastions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To lesen; diminish; curtail; abridge.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retrench</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Retrench
<hw>Re*trench"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To cause or suffer
retrenchment; specifically, to cut down living expenses; <as>as, it is
more reputable to <ex>retrench</ex> than to live
embarrassed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retrenchment</ent>⟦br⟧
